<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/60100745-hayes"><img alt="" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_100x100-259587f1619f5253426a4fa6fb508831.png" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/60100745-hayes">Hayes</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
This answer contains spoilers…
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[
  
    Yes, I think you're right about the allegory. But the ending packs a double-punch as it uses the same dark humor and cringey logic to interpret 9-11 a<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">…more</a>
    Yes, I think you're right about the allegory. But the ending packs a double-punch as it uses the same dark humor and cringey logic to interpret 9-11 as it does for the rest of the book. I don't have the book in front of me so I can't quote the ending, but the gist is that the woman leaping off the tower is "diving into the unknown" in an awakened state. But that's a bit of a forced silver-lining, right? I mean, we do pretty much know what the woman was diving into (certain death). I think the suggestion is that this alternative way of viewing the world is maybe just as asinine as the one before. <a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">(less)</a>
  
 <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</span>
</div>
</div>
