<span id="freeTextContainer11381444200545363589">Hilarious and sad at the same time, weir combination isn&apos;t it... In the beginning, reading about a young lady, beautiful though in a weird mindset, only wanting to sleep and achieving this with a cocktail of all sorts of sleeping/calming medicine, I thought, this is not for me. However, this book is so deliciously weird you keep reading and wondering what is gonna happen next.... and the psychiatrist/therapeut she is seeing.... weird to say the least. Again, hilarious scenes. So I&apos;m hooked and m</span>
  <span id="freeText11381444200545363589" style="display:none">Hilarious and sad at the same time, weir combination isn't it... In the beginning, reading about a young lady, beautiful though in a weird mindset, only wanting to sleep and achieving this with a cocktail of all sorts of sleeping/calming medicine, I thought, this is not for me. However, this book is so deliciously weird you keep reading and wondering what is gonna happen next.... and the psychiatrist/therapeut she is seeing.... weird to say the least. Again, hilarious scenes. So I'm hooked and meantime bought Eileen, another book of Moshfegh shortlisted for the Booker prize 2016. A big four plus rating maybe even five.... And if this isn't an out-of-the-box one, I don't know what is!<br />Recommended for those who love 'out of' genre and can take a bunch of weirdness...<br />Here's some reviews from the media, which sum it up pretty well I think:<br />- Vicously funny… Moshfegh’s writing is as lethally efficient as a flick-knife (The Times)<br />- Another bold assault on the status quo – Prospect<br />- Refined and depraved – New Yorker<br />- Filled with warped desires and dislocation, but also wisdom and warmth – The Economist<br />- Moshfegh specializes in anti-heroines who won’t jump through the normal hoops of womanhood <br /> (Evening Standard)<br />- A deliciously dark and unsettling modern fairy tale. The boldest literary statement of passive resistance since…. – Financial times<br />- M’s blackly funny new noval … hits multiple marks at once: as an artschool prank, a between-the-line stale of displaced grief and pitiless anatomy of gender injustice, it also offers… a dark state-of-America fable. – Observer<br />- You’ll emerge from this darkly hilarious novel not necessarily rested or relaxed but more finely attuned to how delicately fraught the human condition can be. – Marie Claire<br />… ‘the unsettling energy, daring plotting and biting observations… - Time</span>
