    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3721276221" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3721276221" />
    <a title="Lori " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/26424937-lori"><img alt="Lori " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1559993723p2/26424937.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3721276221?book_show_action=true">Jan 01, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lori " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lori " href="/user/show/26424937-lori">Lori </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/26424937-lori?shelf=kindle">kindle</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/26424937-lori?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3721276221" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12399384240768157160">&quot;The ironic and the pathetic are beautifully intertwined in Flaubert’s novel.&quot; <br/><br/>I&apos;m re-reading Madame Bovary for the fourth or sixth time, only this time along with Nabokov&apos;s lecture on it, which I&apos;ve read several times as well but never together. The former is one of my all-time favorite books, the latter one of my two favorite authors, the other being Proust whom Nabokov invoked in his lecture on Madame.<br/><br/>This review has taken me over a month to write because the book took me deep places I never </span>
  <span id="freeText12399384240768157160" style="display:none">"The ironic and the pathetic are beautifully intertwined in Flaubert’s novel." <br /><br />I'm re-reading Madame Bovary for the fourth or sixth time, only this time along with Nabokov's lecture on it, which I've read several times as well but never together. The former is one of my all-time favorite books, the latter one of my two favorite authors, the other being Proust whom Nabokov invoked in his lecture on Madame.<br /><br />This review has taken me over a month to write because the book took me deep places I never expected to go. I became aware of this work or Ottessa Moshfegh while goodreadsing and once I decided I had to read this as my last book of 2020 (though technically I didn't finish until the beginning of 2021 ;) I read no more reviews so I went in expecting satire. And the satire is terrific -- but when I re-read the quote the other day I realized it applies perfectly to My Year of Rest and Relaxation. The images that came to me while reading it and haunt me still are of the masks of comedy and tragedy, along with images from the end, one that is so perfectly conceived and written I'll always be amazed at how Moshfegh pulled it off.<br /><br />The Narrator, who I'll refer to as N because we never learn her name and that is one among many admirable decisions, is very much a satire as are the secondary characters. She's a wealthy Columbia grad, a blonde, beautiful gallery girl who lives where else? off York Avenue on the Upper East Side. And though she's not very good at her insignificant job in one among a pretentious plethora of small galleries which rep artists whose egos are big and work is laughable, Moshfegh endows her with derision for the far wealthier, more beautiful women who are its patrons.<br /><br />"Maggie Kahpour’s father had owned the largest private collection of Picasso doodles in the world, and when he died, she donated them to an abbey in the south of France. The monks named a cheese after her...<br /><br />"Gwen Elbaz-Burke was the grandniece of Ken Burke, the performance artist who was eaten by the shark he kept in his swimming pool, and the daughter of Zara Ali Elbaz, a Syrian princess who was exiled for making a pornographic art film with her German boyfriend, a descendant of Heinrich Himmler.<br /><br />"Zaza Nakazawa was a nineteen-year-old heiress who had written a book about being in a sexual relationship with her aunt, the painter Elaine Meeks."<br /><br />Pretension on pretension and a true portrait of how Manhattan can humble even the highborn and lovely if they allow it to; there's always someone wealthier and lovelier and a never-ending supply of artists whose work is trendy and ludicrous and who make up many small galleries' idea of the Next Big Thing. I was reminded of the now-infamous incident of 2019 at Miami Beach's Art Basel, a very large, prestigious exhibition where serious art collectors mingle with Paris Hilton and the ubiquitous Kardashians. It's possible there are some great pieces but it's never been dear to my heart (and judging by the New York Times article below, not to the writer's either; I enjoyed the New York condescension in the article linked to and it fits quite well with the book). Perhaps you've heard about the banana taped to a wall for which the artist was asking $120,000 and along came the performance artist who removed and ate it. As with the book, some were outraged at the act and others, including me, were amused and delighted.<br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/06/style/art-basel-miami-beach.html">https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/06/st...</a><br /><br />So: N.'s parents have both died recently, the father of illness and the mother soon after a suicide. She has a boyfriend, although I was never sure if that distinction ever applies or is in her own mind because he's a callous ass who treats her with derision even during sex. She doesn't lack self-esteem -- she's suffused with ennui and depression. Her best friend, who is her only friend, isn't a close friend at all but is another wonderfully-written character.<br /><br />After being fired from her lowly job at the gallery (for sleeping) and tiring of Trevor's treatment of her -- which lags behind him being tired of her (which he may always have been) -- N. wants only to sleep for a year, and that year begins in 2000. Time to rework Nab's quote because the ironic and the pathetic are beautifully intertwined in Moshfegh’s novel." N.'s journey is witty, ironic and at times hilarious but she's genuinely depressed (though she's nothing like Emma Bovary); her situation is absolutely ironic and pathetic. <br /><br />Moshfegh brings us the most eccentric psychiatrist I've encountered in literature and if anyone knows a better one, do tell; I want to read that book too. The psychiatrist is quite insane but just what N. needs, one who will give her more and better and actually any pills to keep her sleeping as much as possible for the year; the cost for N. is listening to her ludicrous spoutings.<br /><br />“I’ve heard from several esteemed colleagues in Brazil that regular Infermiterol use can activate a profound tectonic displacement. Followed up with some filigree work using low doses of aspirin and astral projecting, it’s proven to be quite effective in curing solipsistic terror. If that doesn’t work, we will reevaluate."<br /><br />"Prognosticrone. I’ve seen it do wonders, but one of its known side effects is foaming at the mouth. Still, we can’t discount the possibility that maybe—now this is rare, in fact, unprecedented in my professional experience—you’ve been misdiagnosed...And eat a high-dairy meal each day. Did you know that cows can choose to sleep standing up or lying down?"<br /><br />"Psychiatry has come a long way, into the spiritual realm. Into energies. There are deniers, certainly, but they all work for big oil." <br /><br />These gems are sprinkled throughout because N has to show up regularly in order to get more pills.<br /><br />There are visits from Reva, her best friend by default because she's her only friend and really more of an acquaintance. She's a Long Island bulemic, shallow, desperate to get her married lover away from his wife and utterly obsessed with herself. She's pathetic, the source of much irony and Moshfegh's portrayal of Reva flirts with caricature but never consummates it. <br /><br />“This Bush is so much cuter than the last. Isn’t he? Like a rascal puppy." <br />“Reva, I’m not feeling well.”<br /><br />Moshfegh's prose is superb. Every sentence is carefully crafted. She excels at dialogue, imagery -- and foreshadowing. Trevor works at the World Trade Center. If it's not obvious from the date N.'s year begins, the book is seeded with some of the best-written foreshadowing I've encountered in a modern novel. Even with the foreshadowing, which in one lovely bit is deliberately heavy-handed, the ending is impossible to anticipate. I knew from the reviews I'd read that it's a piece of writing those readers reacted to in different ways and sometimes strongly. For this reader, the end is gorgeous and inspired, the last page so well written that it's forever seared in my brain.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12399384240768157160" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


